<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> I am a graphic designer who recently made the upgrade to <br>
Windows 2000 after reading about it's superior memory <br>
management and performance increase for hardware intensive <br>
design applications.<br>
<br>
Though an experienced PC user I find the installation and <br>
setup of any new O/S a daunting experience. Having <br>
formatted my Hard disk with NTFS, installing Windows 2000 <br>
and some design applications I now experience what are <br>
seemingly random crashes. My machine freezes up completely.<br>
<br>
The only other error I am presented with when using my <br>
computer involves a single design application. When the <br>
application's scratch disk is set to the same volume as my <br>
Windows installation I get an error explaining that using <br>
the disk set aside for the Windows primary paging file is <br>
a bad idea. I should instead use a separate volume or <br>
preferably a separate hard disk (I have done so).<br>
<br>
The only clues I have been given as to why my machine is <br>
so temperamental is that the crashes occur most often when <br>
trying to save large files and performing hard disk <br>
intensive operations though this is more of an educated <br>
guess than informed logic.<br>
<br>
I had read that when formatting a drive bad sectors can <br>
result but also that NTFS logs bad sectors and works <br>
around them. I had considered purchasing a new hard disk <br>
but after thoroughly checking my problematic hard disk for <br>
errors I no longer believe that faulty hardware is a <br>
problem (also as the error only occurred after I made the <br>
O/S upgrade).<br>
<br>
I now believe that my problems could be resolved by re-<br>
formatting my hard disk and setting up a primary partition <br>
for Windows 2000 only and a second partition for my <br>
applications though again, this is an educated guess.<br>
<br>
Any assistance would be greatly appreciated though I <br>
understand that it's difficult to diagnose problems <br>
without explicit details.<br>
<br>
I would like to have some reassurance that I might be <br>
correct in my diagnosis before pulling the plug on my <br>
entire system yet again!<br>
<br>
Thank you,<br>
<br>
Nooby</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Hi,<br>
 Something that may influence the way your system works is <br>
whether the 2 harddrives are on the same cable. But more <br>
importantly, whether the machine you have is older. If it <br>
is then you need to get the bios flashed. Sometimes if you <br>
are moving a lot of data back and forth on same channel it <br>
gets corrupted. Since you have added the second drive you <br>
must know how to do the cables. Just unplug the second <br>
drive from the cable and plug it into the other cable <br>
channel. Then go to bios and redetect the drives. Then see <br>
if your problems go away.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> <br>
The drives are on different IDE channels but the problem <br>
persists. Maybe my question should have been:<br>
<br>
&quot;Can having Two drives with a single partition on each <br>
drive cause problems and is the correct partitioning of <br>
the drives crucial to the performance of Windows&quot;.<br>
<br>
I know that to a degree the answer will certainly be &quot;yes&quot; <br>
though I'd like to know whether problems experienced using <br>
single partitioned drives are common.<br>
<br>
</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
My advice:<br>
<br>
a) don't mess with the drive letters assigned automatically when you create<br>
partitions.<br>
b) make sure every directory/folder/volume used by a program has a unique<br>
name<br>
<br>
From remarks in your first post, it sounds as if you tried to use the same<br>
name for both your working directory (folder/partition/volume, or whatever<br>
you call it) and you data storage directory. Don't _ever_ do that. Every<br>
partition _must_ have its own  unique name.<br>
<br>
It's also a good idea for every directory to have a unique name, although you<br>
can get away with, say, &quot;grafix&quot; on two partitions, _if_ you make sure that<br>
all references to these directories also include the correct partition<br>
letters. Unfortunately, some software doesn't bother insisting on knowing<br>
drive letters, but assumes that everything is on C: (since MS wants you to<br>
have One Big Partition on One Big Drive....) Thus, the software will look for<br>
data in the &quot;current&quot; directory. If that happens to be on the wrong drive,<br>
you may be in trouble. At the least, you may &quot;lose&quot; data, since it won't be<br>
where you expect it. I would ensure that any directories used by a particular<br>
piece of software have distinct names.<br>
<br>
As for the effects of partitioning (or not), it seems to depend on the kind<br>
of partitioning (Fdisk) and formatting (done when you Fdisk, or done by the<br>
OS) software you used, since that software assigns the partition type codes.<br>
W2K is (quite properly) fussy about partition types, but also it lets you<br>
&quot;reassign&quot; drive/partition letters. IMO it's a bad idea to do this, since it<br>
doesn't really reassign anything, it merely creates aliases. OTOH, some users<br>
have found no problems doing this.<br>
<br>
Your first drive is drive zero. Its first partition  will be C:, and must be<br>
primary (your Fdisk software may call it bootable, or ask you to set it<br>
bootable, etc.) This where W2K must be - it can't be anywhere else.<br>
<br>
Your second drive is drive one. Its first partition should be D:, and<br>
primary. (If you want, you can put another OS here, such as OS2 or Linux or<br>
whatever.)<br>
<br>
If you now create additional partitions on one or both of your drives, they<br>
will be lettered E;, F:, etc. The rule is that primary partitions are<br>
lettered before extended (or logical) partitions. EG, if you have a primary<br>
and an extended partitionÕ{ùw¿»l,ﬂL∑?|3p Ï¬ on drive zero, and one on drive one, then the three<br>
partitions will be: C: (primary on zero), D: (primary on one), and E:<br>
(extended on zero.) These letters are assigned by Fdisk and BIOS, not the OS,<br>
which merely &quot;recognises&quot; the drives. There's more to it than this, but it<br>
does<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Okay...<br>
<br>
I only have one partition per drive (therefor Windows <br>
detects two drives). It would seem that to resolve the <br>
problem of application scratch disks conflicting with <br>
Win2K's paging (swap) file I need to create a second <br>
partition on my primary drive (or indeed a volume, as the <br>
problemmatic applications specifies, which was new along <br>
with &quot;dynamic disks&quot; to Win2K).<br>
<br>
My solution to the problem as it stands would be this:<br>
<br>
To reformat the drive and create two partitions on my <br>
primary hard disk. The first partition would be used for <br>
the Windows installation and it's paging file only. I <br>
would then use the second partition for everything else <br>
(applications etc). This seems to be a probable solution <br>
to my problems, if only at least that it would rectify my <br>
application based errors, which I believe are a symptom of <br>
the main fault.<br>
<br>
There are a few problems with this solution:<br>
<br>
1. I'd have to get wipe my machine clean. This is always a <br>
problem with such a drastic solution, I wouldn't mind if I <br>
could garauntee that a solution would work. My machine is <br>
crucial to my work and to loose it for any length of time <br>
would pose a problem, again I'd face this if I could <br>
garauntee that a solution works.<br>
<br>
2. The idea of setting up two partitions on a single drive <br>
in contrary to the way I use my machine. I like keeping <br>
the &quot;chain&quot; as simple as possible and up until now have <br>
seen no reason to add more &quot;links&quot; by splitting the drive <br>
into sections. My theory is that the more simple the <br>
structure of my computer, the easier it will be to <br>
diagnose prblems and the less will go wrong.<br>
<br>
</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<br>
I hope this provides enough information to start trying to find solutions to my current problem.<br>
